==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*bauwa-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''buwa'' (Frisian ''bouwje''), Old Saxon ''[[būan]]'' (Dutch ''[[bouwen]]''), Old High German ''[[būan]]'' (German ''[[bauen]]''), Old Norse ''[[búa]]'', Gothic [[𐌱𐌰𐌿𐌰𐌽]]
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /bu:an/
===Verb===
'''būan''' (class 1 weak)

# to [[live]] or [[dwell]]
#:''He bude on East-Englum'': he lived with the East Angles.  (''Anglo-Saxon Chronicle'')
# to [[inhabit]], to [[occupy]]
#:''Ne mæg mon meduseld buan'': a man may not occupy the mead-bench,  (''Beowulf'')

